            <biogHist>
                <p>Calum [Malcolm] MacPhie was born to Donald MacPhie, crofter, and Annie née
                    MacNeil. The earliest recording of him is in the 1841 Census, aged 10, living
                    with his parents and siblings on Berneray, Barra Head. He had an older sister
                    Catherine (12), and three younger siblings: John (12), Donald (5) and Anne (3).
                    The 1852 Census records him staying at one of the farmhouses as a servant and
                    farm labourer. Ten years later he had rejoined his parents and brothers who had
                    now moved to Mingulay. In November 1866 Malcolm married Mary MacNeil, daughter
                    of Donald and Catherine née MacNeil from Tangasdal. They remained on Mingulay
                    where Malcolm continued as a fisherman. In 1871 he now had son, Donald  (3), and
                    the family was living in a croft with two rooms with windows. By 1881 he had a
                    further four children: Catherine (9), Neil (7), Roderick (5) and Mary (3), all
                    at school. In 1891 only two children were staying with Malcolm and his wife,
                    Donald and Catherine, Donald was a fisherman, Catherine was a domestic servant.
                    In 1901, it was their other daughter Mary who was now staying with them. It
                    shows that Malcolm and his daughter Mary could speak both Gaelic and English,
                    whereas the mother only spoke Gaelic. </p>
                <p>Malcolm died in January 1908 from senile decay, he was survived by his wife. His
                    nephew Donald MacPhie signed the death certificate.</p>
                <p>In 1901 Malcolm met Carmichael and recounts the story of two crows fighting. </p>
